value.value: Any cataract in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the CRYGC gene.
A retinopathy caused by a variant in the X-linked gene, RPGR.
A retinopathy caused by biallelic variants in the AIPL1 gene.
Any glycogen storage disease in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the PHKA2 gene, with no PHK in liver, but normal activity in erythrocytes.
An inherited susceptibility or predisposition to developing Asperger sydrome.
A retinopathy caused by a heterozygous gain of function or dominant-negative variant or in the GUCY2D gene.
A retinopathy caused by variants in the X-linked gene, RP2.
A retinopathy caused by bialleleic variants in the RDH5 gene, often involving flecks in the retina.
A retinopathy caused by bialleleic variants in the RLBP1 gene, often involving flecks in the retina.
A retinopathy caused by biallelic variants in the LCA5 gene.
A retinopathy caused by biallelic variants in the CNGB3 gene.
A retinopathy caused by biallelic variants in the AFT6 gene.
A retinopathy caused by biallelic variants in the RAB28 gene.

label.value: FLVCR1-related retinopathy with or without ataxia

value.value: A disorder characterized by retinopathy with ataxia in most patients, caused by biallelic variants in the FLVCR1 gene.
An autosomal dominant vitreoretinopathy caused by variants in the CAPN5 gene. Additional features, such as developmental delay and hypotonia, have been reported in some patients.
A ciliopathy caused by biallelic variants in the CEP290 gene.
A retinopathy caused by a heterozygous gain of function variant in the RPE65 gene.
A retinopathy caused by biallelic variants in the GUCY2D gene.
Any inherited retinal dystrophy in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the GUCY2D gene.

A complex neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by a neonatal onset of recurrent seizures, an abnormal neonatal electroencephalographic background with multifocal epileptiform discharges, excessive discontinuity, and/or burst-suppression patterns, and encephalopathy. Seizures may be pharmacoresistant or responsive. Developmental delays persist but vary in severity. In some individuals, subsequent evolution to other epileptic encephalopathy syndromes (e.g. West syndrome) may occur.

A disorder characterized onset at birth of profound encephalopathy with hypotonia, Respiratory insufficiency central hypoventilation, a persistent suppression burst pattern of EEG background, and recurrent bouts of myoclonus that are not accompanied by epileptic discharges on electroencephalography. Evolution to pharmacoresistant seizures is common and continued profound global developmental delay.
An instance of achalsia that is caused by an inherited genomic modification in an individual.

Any syndrome in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the MECOM gene. MECOM-associated syndrome has a variable phenotypic pattern, ranging from isolated radioulnar synostosis with no or mild hematological involvement to severe bone marrow failure without obvious skeletal abnormalities. The clinical picture can also include clinodactyly, cardiac and renal malformations, B-cell deficiency, amegakaryocytic thrombocytopenia, and presenile hearing loss.
A male infertility disease characterized by the absence of any measurable level of sperm in semen.
An inherited susceptibility or predisposition to developing nicotine dependence.

label.value: short stature and advanced bone age, with or without early-onset osteoarthritis and/or osteochondritis dissecans

value.value: A rare genetic skeletal disorder characterized clinically by abnormal chondro-skeletal development, disproportionate short stature and skeletal deformation mainly affecting the knees, hips, ankles and elbows with onset generally in late childhood or adolescence.

label.value: methylmalonic aciduria and/or homocystinuria, cblD type

value.value: An autosomal recessive inborn disorder of cobalamin metabolism caused by biallelic variants in MMADHC. Depending on the type and location of variants in MMADHC, patients may present with methylmalonic aciduria, homocystinuria, or both. MMADHC has been reported to result in the cblD complementation group of cobalamin disorders.

An autosomal recessive lysosomal disease caused by biallelic loss of function variants in the SMPD1 gene. Clinical symptoms in affected individuals occur along a continuum. At the severe end of the spectrum are individuals historically diagnosed with Niemann-Pick disease type A (the neurovisceral form), which is characterized by hepatosplenomegaly with rapid neurological deterioration leading to death in the first few years of life. At the milder end of the spectrum are individuals historically diagnosed with Niemann-Pick disease type B, a later-onset, chronic visceral form, characterized by progressive visceral organ symptoms including hepatosplenomegaly and pulmonary insufficiency, and survival into adulthood. In addition, some affected individuals present with an intermediate phenotype, Niemann-Pick disease type A/B.

label.value: complex neurodevelopmental disorder with or without congenital anomalies

value.value: A complex neurodevelopmental disorder that involves more than one phenotype associated with the central nervous system, including but not limited to intellectual disability, autism, and seizures (epilepsy), in addition to one or more structural or functional anomaly(ies) that develops prenatally.

A patterned dystrophy of the retinal pigment epithelium characterized by abnormal accumulation of lipofuscin in a butterfly-shaped distribution at the retinal pigment epithelium level. Patients manifest with a slowly progressive loss of vision that often only becomes apparent in old age.
A congenital myopathy in which a family of 6 siblings presented in infancy the picture of 'amyotonia congenita' and later in life a nonprogressive myopathy.
X-linked form of anosmia, isolated congenital.
Coughing, wheezing, or shortness of breath that is triggered by allergens, infection, or other irritants.
Abnormally low level of 25-hydroxyvitamin D in the blood.

label.value: lissencephaly spectrum disorder with complex brainstem malformation

value.value: A lissencephaly spectrum disorder that manifests as posterior predominant pachygyria (ranging from mild severity to classic lissencephaly) and brainstem malformations which include brainstem dysplasia (typically with reduced anteroposterior thickness and transverse broadening of the pons/medulla) and midline crossing defects (anterior commissure, transverse pontine fibers, pyramidal tract, callosum hypoplasia).

label.value: disorder of peptide and amine metabolism

value.value: An inherited metabolic disease that has its basis in the disruption of peptide and/or amine metabolic process.
An instance of ichthyosis vulgaris in which the disease presentation is mild in severity. Heterozygote FLG mutation carriers often have mild manifestations.
An instance of ichthyosis vulgaris in which the disease presentation is severe in severity. Homozygous FLG mutation carriers often have more severe manifestations.
An inherited susceptibility or predisposition to developing acquired partial lipodystrophy.
An inherited metabolic disease that has its basis in the disruption of methylamine metabolic process.

label.value: brain malformations with or without urinary tract defects

value.value: A brain disorder caused by pathogenic variants in NFIA that is characterized by developmental delay, corpus callosum agenesis/hypoplasia and craniofacial dysmorphism, such as macrocephaly (caused by hydrocephalus or ventriculomegaly), low-set ears, anteverted nostrils and micrognathia. Urinary tract defects (e.g. vesicoureteral reflux, urinary incontinence) are also frequently associated. Other reported variable manifestations include hypotonia, tethered spinal cord, Chiari type I malformation and seizures.

definition.value: NFIA is one of the genes involved in the 1p31p32 microdeletion syndrome, which presents with very similar features.

value.value: A form of drug-resistant tuberculosis that is resisant to rifampicin with or without resistance to other antitubercular medications.
Diminished production of adrenocortical hormones due to autoimmune destruction of the adrenal glands.

Tuberculosis caused by primary infection of or reactivation of latent Mycobacterium tuberculosis. Active tuberculosis characterized by clinical manifestation and active symptoms compatible with tuberculosis, and is distinct from latent tuberculosis infection that occurs without signs or symptoms of active disease.

A type of drug-resistant tuberculosis that is resistant to any fluoroquinolone, and at least one of three second-line injectable drugs (capreomycin, kanamycin, and amikacin), in addition to resistance to rifampicin and isoniazid.

A type of drug-resistant tuberculosis that is resistant to all first- and second-line antitubercular drugs tested (isoniazid, rifampicin, streptomycin, ethambutol, pyrazinamide, ethionamide, para-aminosalicylic acid, cycloserine, ofloxacin, amikacin, ciprofloxacin, capreomycin, kanamycin).
A vitreoretinopathy caused by variants in the TSPAN12 gene.

Any neurodevelopmental disorder in which the cause of the disease is a mutation in the KCNH1 gene. Variants in KCNH1 cause significant neurodevelopmental disabilities that lie along a phenotypic spectrum ranging from non-syndromic to syndromic. The most common phenotypes associated with variants in KCNH1 include intellectual disability, seizures, hypotonia, absence or hypoplasia of nails, and gingival enlargement. Hypoplastic terminal phalanges of fingers and toes, proximal placement and long thumb, and long toes present less frequently.
Acne that occurs in an adult.
